name: Birthday Dinners That Won't Break the Bank

text.text: Birthday Dinners That Won't Break the Bank

Birthdays can be a bit hectic, especially if some of your friends' bonuses are bigger than others' salaries. Rather than assuming everyone wants to make as big a deal out of your birthday as you do... why not choose somewhere unassuming? Like this lot, for example...

tip.text:
Know Ben Chapman? Well you should. He's the mighty talented chef behind Soho favourite and spice paradise Kiln. Smoking Goat has a more relaxed vibe, taking inspo from the quick snacks and comfort food served in the late-night Bangkok canteens. Flavours are sour and spicy, though not quite Kiln levels and cocktails are appropriately simple and refreshing.

Smoking Goat may not be a showstopper but it's the perfect spot for a squad dinner. In an ideal world you'll go in a group of four or so, you'll order a couple beers, the barbecued goat and turmeric massaman curry, and some sides (we're thinking kale, sambal aubergine and lardo fried rice). You'll scoff the lot then leave plenty full with change from a £20 note. Unless you want to make your own decisions, in which case you should get off this app, mate.

text.text: From the team behind Kiln, Smoking Goat dishes up spice-heavy plates inspired by late-night Bangkok canteens. You can book for up to ten, order a few beers and share some of the larger plates for maximum value. We'd grab a barbecued goat and turmeric massaman curry, the smoked brisket drunken noodles and some sexy sides.

tip.text:
Lee Tiernan has certainly carved a niche for himself with this death-metal-themed Turkish restaurant - an unruly combination that he’s pulled off effortlessly. Cast your gaze around the room and you’ll find no shortage of things to look at: penis graffiti on the floors, a wood-oven adorned with portraits of Kiss, and Tiernan himself, covered in tats, looking like someone from north of The Wall.

But Black Axe is far from all style: the lamb offal flatbread is an absolute necessity - think warm, earthy flavours offset by punchy pickled onions and perfectly fluffy bread straight from the wood-fired oven (along with its resulting aromas). The cocktails, meanwhile, are well mixed and as strong as an ox. Be warned, however, the loud heavy metal makes this a poor choice for a catch-up with your nan.

text.text: We'd recommend this absolute gem for a smaller group as you can't book. But grab a table and you'll be chuffed to bits with zesty cocktails, succulent meats and heavy metal music (if you like heavy metal music, of course). The lamb offal flat bread is an absolute necessity – think warm, earthy flavours, offset by punchy, pickled onions - yum.

tip.text:
Stumbling down unlit, unnamed side-alleys in Peckham is the kinda thing your dear mother told you not to do, but hey, you're an adult now: you pay council tax, you get excited about new kitchen appliances, and you sometimes don't buy the cheapest wine in Tescos.

Another reason to ignore your mum is that occasionally at the bottom of these side-alleys are elusive BYOB Kurdish spots, complete with upstairs Shisha bars, covered al fresco dining, and big ol' vegan or meat sharing platers. Yada‘s is one such spot, and it‘s bulging with delicious salads, Kubbas (rice patties stuffed with lamb and nuts), hummus, and tasty shreds of succulent chicken or lamb shawarma. It's cheap, the atmosphere is buzzy, and the whole experience will be sprinkled with the smug satisfaction that you discovered this hidden gem (with a helping hand from us).

text.text: Stumbling down unlit, unnamed side-alleys in Peckham isn't always advisable, but occasionally you'll find elusive BYOB Kurdish spots at the end of them - Yada's comes complete with an upstairs Shisha bar, covered al fresco dining, and big ol' vegan or meat sharing platers bulging with salads, kubbas (rice patties stuffed with lamb and nuts), hummus, and tasty shreds of succulent chicken or lamb shawarma.

tip.text:
Is the rapid spread of the 'small, sharing plates' trend doing your nut in? Well what better way to revolt than by getting rid of plates all together? Andu is the perfect spot to do so - this Kingsland Road gem is one of those no-bullshit places that serves up simple and delicious Ethiopian food which also happens to be 100% vegan. It's BYOB, the staff are bloody lovely and it’s damn cheap to boot. And as is the way with Ethiopian cuisine, the food is served atop injera bread (sour fermented pancake).

We’d recommend grabbing a pal and rolling down to Dalston to try the ‘sampler’, a selection of six dishes served atop injera or rice - perfect for two to share and yours for only £12. If you’re in the area and dining Han Solo, you can get an individual sampler to take away for a fiver. So leave any vibe-snipers at home and get yourself down to Andu before you can say “yemisir wot” (Ethiopian red lentil stew).

text.text: Perfect for a large veggie group, a night at Andu cafe will leave you with change from a £20 note. This Kingsland Road gem is one of those no-bullshit places that serves up simple and delicious Ethiopian food which also happens to be 100% vegan. It's BYOB, the staff are bloody lovely and the food is simple, honest and served atop injera bread (spongy sour fermented pancake).

tip.text:
This taqueria has all the spice of a real roadside joint without any of the bowel anxiety. Work your way through a veggie jackfruit taco, topped with crunchy sweet potato; or a taco packed with slow-cooked lamb topped with coriander and onions; and a steak quesadilla perhaps? It's important you know it wouldn't be weird to order one of every taco. No shame; be free, young warrior.

The drinks are just as cray as the colourful decor. Get off on lime, watermelon or cucumber margaritas (with your choice of tequila or mezcal) or try your hand at a 'Michelada', which is basically a beer-based Bloody Mary. Curious aren't you pussy cat?

Ps: It's £2 tacos on Tuesdays. Hells yeah.

text.text: This taqueria has all the spice of a real Mexican roadside joint without any of the bowel anxiety. Think slow-cooked lamb topped with coriander and onion tacos, veggie jackfruit tacos and more. Food is cheap, margs come in jugs and chunes are bountiful. Yep it's a real good time joint that just happens to serve up some succulent Mexican grub.

tip.text:
It’s impossible to breeze past Persepolis without at least a second glance. The canary-yellow facade frames large windows that peek into a topsy-turvy world decorated with Middle Eastern string instruments; cans of food adorned in Arabic; hookahs; spices and other miscellanea. This cafe-cum-deli is like a psychedelic shouk, an Peckham OG that’s long been serving the community with hard-to-find ingredients and veg-based Persian cooking.

Opened in 1999 by Sally Butcher - whose wild cloud of red hair is instantly recognisable to any Peckhamite - Persepolis evolved from a shop to a DIY restaurant. Bring your own booze and hunker down for a vegetarian feast, letting Sally feed you course upon course of Middle Eastern delights - all changed daily based on Sally’s whim. Caution: loose trousers are a must.

text.text: You think of Persian food and you think of meat, so a veggie Persian restaurant seems a little odd, but hear us out. Part grocery and craft store, part restaurant, this little goodie is perfect for a get together. The menu changes daily and features all sorts of sharing meze and baklava bites. Bigger groups will need to get the party menu which rocks up to £15-20 - pretty nice, eh?

tip.text:
Time to come over all Tony Soprano at Ciao Bella: a buzzy place of unadulterated, carb-loaded Italian goodness. Going strong for 30 years now, you get the sense that this place hasn't changed much/at all; which is really its charm. Blunt old-timer waiters grunt about the place, a resident pianist flexes his fingers now and again, and old movie posters and black and white pictures cover every inch of wall.

But let's talk food and the huge menu full of flavoursome, generously-sized favourites: big and tasty 12" pizzas, insane portions of rich pasta every which way, and hefty meat and fish dishes. Whatever you get, you'll likely be needing an extra large doggie bag or a stretcher to take your happy, bloated body out of this Italo original. Just don't forget to have a sip of limoncello as you're carried out.

text.text: Not many restaurants handle group dinners as graciously as Ciao Bella. They know what you're about, they know you're getting a little tipsy, you've forgotten your order already and you want extra limoncello. They know what you're like and they handle it all with an aloof Italian sort-of smile and a great big bowl of carbs.

tip.text: Here we have a family-run restaurant that gives peeps the authentic Pakistani food they want, with banging curries, kebabs and other treats. Their portions are generous, the flavours are on point, the price is nice and the casual setting makes it the perfect place to munch out hard and forget any table etiquette. Get the lamb chops if you know what's good for you. Oh, and it's BYO everyday with no corkage fee - double score!

text.text: Here we have a family-run restaurant that gives peeps the authentic Pakistani food they want, with banging curries, kebabs and other treats. Their portions are generous, the flavours are on point, the price is nice and the casual setting (it's a fairly drab canteen) makes it the perfect place to munch out hard and forget any table etiquette. Oh and it's BYOB, baby.

tip.text:
It's take three for Yard Sale with their third London site. Grab one of these scrummy pizzas to eat in the rear dining room's comfy booths, sit on a stool at the front or take one home to eat alone in your dressing gown and slippers. What's so good about their pizzas? Is it the double fermented dough? Is it the fresh toppings? Probably both, Sherlock.

If you can make it all the way out to Walthamstow at the weekend, and you're feeling brave, you might want to try the brunch pizza (exclusive to this site). Yep brunch pizza, thats a thing, why not eh? It comes topped with crumbled chorizo, avocado and lime, fresh spinach and a runny egg you can dip soldiers of crisp garlic, rosemary & sea salted pizza bread (with or without Marmite!). Marmite?!

text.text: Yard Sale's Walthamstow outpost is the biggest of the four, with plenty of space for your friends and their bums. What's so good about their pizzas? Is it the double fermented dough? Is it the fresh toppings? Probably both, Sherlock. And if you're into sharing, the 18 inchers are cheese-drizzlingly good value.

tip.text:
Gallipoli restaurant (just down the road at 102 Upper Street) did so bloody well they decided to open another. Like any younger sister, round two is slightly more into partying - making it the perfect place for a group dinner and a little traditional belly dancing.

Food remains simple and delish' with plenty of Turkish and Mediterranean goodies - from tasty meze morsels like baba ganoush, dolma, and falafel; to hunks of marinated meat on mounds of rice and salad. Sit amongst hanging lanterns, Persian movie stars and red lights for an authentically good time.

text.text: Let Gallipoli Again's fragrant smells of sizzling meat lure you in to a restaurant filled with stained-glass lanterns and happy punters enjoying their bargain grub. The menu is a selection of Turkish and Mediterranean goodies, from tasty meze morsels like baba ganoush, dolma, and falafel; to hunks of marinated meat on mounds of rice and salad. Groups can grab a party menu of three courses for £20 per person.

tip.text:
This isn't your normal Chinese restaurant. There’s no MSG or sweet & sour chicken to be found here, oh no - instead, this place focuses on Uyghur dishes, from the Muslim ethnic group found in western-most China. The cuisine is a curious concoction of Chinese, Middle Eastern & Persian influences, and the menu features typical Uyghur dishes such as ‘Ganbian Chaomian’ and 'Ququre'. There are also some more daring dishes like marinated cow's stomach, which we've heard is delish, if you can stomach it...

The insides are decorated with wall hangings, doppa hats and miniature musical instruments, which adds to its curious ambience. It’s also a family run business, and there’s some serious convivial vibes making you feel nice and homely. Heads up, it's a Halal restaurant so don't expect any pork or alcohol - but what they lack here, we can assure they make up elsewhere.

text.text: Etles isn't your usual Chinese restaurant, it focuses on Uyghur dishes from the Muslim ethnic group found in western-most China. The cuisine is a curious concoction of Chinese, Middle Eastern and Persian influences. Go for big sharing plates like the Do Pan Ji - chicken with bell peppers and potatoes cooked in garlic, ginger, soya sauce and other fresh herbs, served with homemade pasta. Heads up, it's halal so don't expect any pork or alcohol.
